) The report sets out the specific assumptions that Mr Salter has been asked to make as to Seven's strategy, as follows:

 'It was proposed by the Seven Network that the integrated media company would: 



 (a) utilise rights to premium content, skills, production facilities and brand in a complementary manner across a number of different media and distribution channels; 

 (b) maximise the value of broadcasting rights by offering the widest possible distribution of content to the holders of sporting and other rights; 

 (c) derive revenue from integrated advertising packages across various platforms and distributions outlets; 

 (d) develop effective and deeper links with viewers and thereby create greater opportunities for advertisers through content enhancements and interactivity by utilising new technologies including digital interactive and multicasting transmission, broadband internet services and audio-video telephony; 

 (e) capitalise on a competitive advantage previously held over other potential entrants, particularly in respect of emerging distribution channels and digital content enhancements; and 

 (f) derive future profits as an integrated media company in a converging media, telecommunication and broadcasting market comprising carriage providers, content services and facilities for the provision of carriage services.

14 Seven's submissions summarise Mr Salter's analysis of that methodology in terms that I am content to adopt for present purposes:


 '(a) first, Mr Salter defines media companies as coming within a number of discrete industries and gives reasons for his opinion that it is appropriate to consider acquisitions of companies in those industries for the purposes of his valuation; 

 (b) secondly, he sets out the types of transactions he has considered, the source of his information about them (namely, Bloomberg), the use of Bloomberg by finance industry professionals in his area of expertise, and the criteria he applied in discarding certain transactions; 

 (c) thirdly, he divides the remaining transactions into two categories, strategic or financial, on the basis of whether the information provided by Bloomberg showed the acquirer to be in a similar industry to the target company; 





 (d) fourthly, using the deal premium provided by Bloomberg for each transaction (that is, the price paid above the target [company's] market capitalisation) and after excluding outliers, Mr Salter calculates the median and average deal premium for strategic transactions and financial transactions; and 





 (e) fifthly, Mr Salter concludes that strategic acquirers paid a median deal premium of 21.5 per cent and an average deal premium of 24.4 per cent, while strategic acquirers paid a median deal premium of 6.6 per cent and an average deal premium of 9.6 per cent'.

Seven summarises the second component as follows:


 '(a) first, Mr Salter calculates the difference between strategic acquirers' and financial acquirers' deal premiums as being around 15 per cent and allowing, as a matter of prudence, for a variation of up to one third above or below that figure comes up with a range of between 10 per cent and 20 per cent; 





 (b) secondly, he reasons that strategic acquirers of media industry companies pay a higher deal premium than financial acquirers (as his empirical analysis suggests) because strategic acquirers, being media companies themselves, derive IMC benefits from the transactions while financial acquirers do not; 





 (c) thirdly, he considers that strategic acquirers quantify the incremental IMC benefits which they expect to derive from a transaction on the basis that those benefits are likely to be proportional to the IMC benefits they obtain from their existing operations; 

 (d) fourthly, from the second and third steps in this reasoning process, Mr Salter infers that the difference between strategic acquirers' and financial acquirers' deal premiums is likely to be a reasonable proxy for the premium placed on a media company by virtue of the fact that it is an IMC (hence he refers to the range of between 10 per cent and 20 per cent as the "IMC premium range"); and 





 (e) fifthly, from this follows Mr Salter's opinion that it is reasonable to state that the IMC premium which Seven lost by virtue of the facts that it was unable to pursue its IMC strategy through C7 was between 10 per cent and 20 per cent of its market capitalisation'.

This is due to its ability to aggregate large numbers of potential viewers; 





 (2) the Seven Network either possessed, or was in a good position to obtain, key content rights, particularly sports rights and Australian drama, and had the expertise and facilities to create an own high quality content; 

 (3) this provided Seven Network with a competitive advantage over other potential entrants, particularly in respect of the emerging distribution channels; and 

 (4) the Seven Network had a strong existing brand, as well as established media personalities, with associated audience loyalty, which could be leveraged and exploited on new platforms.
